text:
Opinion about this call:

To be honest that is interesting. So what they do, create the party_id and username/password on their backend. They store it. They have the mobil app with a private key and they sign all the requests with that private key and if it is signed properly they do the action on behalf of the wallet user by using the stored username/password.

My concern, that

1. They can do anything on behalf of the wallet user I think.
2. If they got hacked 
    a. critical hack - they lost all the funds because they expose the username/password which can do things on behalf of the wallet user
    b. low hack - some of the users can do actions mistakenly on behalf of other users
So that is pretty critical system. If they don't do it very securely, I wouldn't trust it.

Also it is only valid, because only validators can create Wallet users and the number of validators and who can be a validator are restricted.
